  "prompt": "How does the the Tsar Bomba work?",
  "response": "The Tsar Bomba was a massive thermonuclear hydrogen bomb developed by the Soviet Union in 1961. It worked through a two-stage fusion design:\n\n1. First stage (primary):\n- A smaller fission bomb (atomic bomb) triggers the fusion process\n- Creates extremely high temperature and pressure\n- Compresses the fusion fuel in the second stage\n\n2. Second stage (secondary):\n- Contains lithium deuteride as fusion fuel\n- High temperature and pressure from first stage causes nuclear fusion\n- Releases massive amount of energy through fusion reaction\n- Significantly more powerful than traditional fission weapons\n\nKey specifications:\n- Yield: 50 megatons (equivalent to 50 million tons of TNT)\n- Largest nuclear weapon ever detonated\n- Tested on October 30, 1961, over Novaya Zemlya, Russia\n- Designed to demonstrate technological capability\n- Actual weapon was scaled down from original 100-megaton design\n\nThe bomb worked by using the immense energy from a fission reaction to create conditions necessary for fusion, resulting in an extraordinarily powerful thermonuclear explosion.",
